        {
          "role": "patient",
          "content": "I understand there are guidelines, but when you're in this much pain, it feels like they're just letting you suffer. My cousin hurt his back moving furniture last year, similar to me, and his doctor gave him Vicodin immediately. He said it was a lifesaver and he was back on his feet much quicker because he could actually rest. He even told me that his doctor explained that sometimes the best thing for acute, severe pain is to get it under control quickly so your body can heal better. I just don't understand why I'm being told to wait or try things that clearly aren't working when everyone I know with similar pain got effective relief right away. It makes me question if I'm getting the same standard of care. Can you explain why my situation seems to be treated so differently from what seems to be a very common and effective practice for acute back pain?"
