        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I understand your frustration and the importance of managing your pain effectively. You're right that severe pain can be very distressing, and prompt relief is a priority for many patients. While some studies do support the use of stronger medications in specific cases, current clinical guidelines generally recommend cautious use of opioids, especially for acute back pain, due to the risks of dependence and side effects.\n\nResearch suggests that early use of opioids may not necessarily lead to better long-term outcomes and can sometimes increase the risk of chronic pain or dependency when not carefully managed. That\u2019s why we typically reserve these medications for cases where other treatments haven't provided relief, and they are prescribed with close monitoring.\n\nWhat I can do is develop a comprehensive pain management plan tailored to your needs, which might include a short course of a more potent medication if appropriate, along with physical therapy, and possibly other interventions. I strongly advise you to see a healthcare provider in person to evaluate your situation thoroughly. Would you like help arranging an appointment or discuss alternative strategies to ease your pain?"
        },
        {
          "role": "patient",
